sec.p:
For annotating changes in the state of cellular differentiation, there are two options. The first is to use an appropriate GO term, but because the GO includes less than 50 cell types, it cannot (and was not intended) to do justice to developmental anatomy. A better option, therefore, is to use the higher-level GO term “cell differentiation” and combine it with two terms from the Cell-Type Ontology. The annotation would thus be \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}
$$ <{\rm cell \, type} \, 1><\, cell \, differentiation><{\rm cell \, type} \, 2> $$\end{document}

In the case of metanephric mesenchyme being induced to form nephron epithelium, the annotation is \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}
$$ <{\rm mesenchyme}><\, cell \, differentiation><{\rm duct \, epithelium} > $$\end{document}

or, using the appropriate IDs from the two ontologies: \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}
$$ {{\rm{ < CL:0000134 >< }}GO:0030154{\rm{ >< CL:0000068 > }}} $$\end{document}
